\begin_layout Standard
A risk-neutral seller solves the dynamic optimization problem to maximize
 the average profit flow.
 The seller faces the sequence of jobs arriving at Poisson rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\betaa$
\end_inset

, for each job observes the platform's signal 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and chooses to accept or reject it.
 See 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:Sellers-repeated-search"

\end_inset

 for the illustration.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(s,y)=\int_{X}\pi(x,y)ds(x)$
\end_inset

 the seller 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

's expected profit if he accepts a job with signal 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $V(y)$
\end_inset

 be the average profit flow when the seller of type 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 acts optimally (the value function)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For example, if a seller earns $1 on each job, and the time interval between
 starting consequent jobs is 2, then 
\begin_inset Formula $V(y)=1/2$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $v(s,y)$
\end_inset

 be the value of a new job with signal 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 includes the option value of rejecting the job and the opportunity cost
 of accepting.
 The value of a new job is zero if the seller rejects it, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(s,y)-\tau V(y)$
\end_inset

 if he accepts it, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau V(y)$
\end_inset

 is the opportunity cost of accepting due to being unavailable for time
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $v(s,y)=\max\{0,\pi(s,y)-\tau V(y)\}$
\end_inset

